text:
thank you guys for following me and acknowledging that we need to talk and foster open dialogue on this issue. 
i think the battle against both sexual harassment & abuse and the related trauma is half won if we as a society can come together and encourage people to feel safe enough.

i would love to know your opinions on your experiences, feedback, and about what more we can do.please feel free to drop a comment or message me. 
a big thank you to all of you. 
#sexualharassment #letustalk #speakup #survivor #staystrong #metoo #metooindia #sexualabuse #childabuse #opendialogue

text:
#metoo. the hashtag now known world wide was started by tarana burke in 2006. while working at just be inc., a nonprofit she founded in 2003 that focused on the overall well-being of young women of color, tarana began assuring survivors of sexual assault that they were not alone - she was also a survivor. the hashtag gained popularity on october 15, 2017 when actress alyssa milano encouraged people to tweet the phrase if they were survivors. soon, more that 12 million people across twitter were using the hashtag and shedding light on the assaults. #metoo has not only given survivors a sense of solidarity, but it has given a platform to those who want to tell their story. it has brought attention to the very public assaults that the world had been ignoring. tarana started a movement in 2006, one that has continued to change rape culture and how the world responds to sexual assault. #throwbackthursday #igniteyourinnergoldenbear

text:
#metoo (part 4/4 of answering questions whose existence has convinced me that i'm never going to be able to speak up. to read the entire list in one go, please click on the link in my bio.) .
.
.
.
#8: some woman online talked about how her boyfriend hit her. and another one about how her boss spoke to her suggestively. where is the sexual assualt in this? how is this #metoo

the #metoo movement, like i said earlier, is a fight against systematic patriarchal constructs that make us scared everyday. think about it this way: it's about any violence committed where the imbalance in the cultural and societal powers of the genders play a role. an abusive man hitting a woman believes he is superior to her, which is why he has the authority to do what he does. the boss situation is even more messed up, because first of all, he sees his employee as consumable because of her femininity, and because here, the employee-boss power structure plays an additional role. there can be no sure consent in a relationship with such a tainted balance scale of power. in the boss-employee dynamic, it's institutional power. in the abuser-abused dynamic, it's psychological.
.
.
.
#9: why do anonymous accounts hold credibility at all? 
because of you. because you make life living hell for women who gather the courage after an intense amount of work and name someone. because sometimes, there is still a power imbalance and the women doesn't feel secure enough to speak up, but still wants to, to prevent future possible victims- and bring to light who the man really is.
.
.
.

#10: oh. i just realized i have been wrong about everything. i'm so sorry. what can i do to help?

support the survivors. point out when someone around you objectifies, boasts about, or harasses a woman. start having higher standards for what kind of people you want to associate with. don't pass off things as locker room talk or 'boys will be boys'. answer all these questions for whoever is the next person to even casually discuss them them with you. but most importantly, once again, support the survivors. and promise to help build a place where they wouldn't be any.
#feminism #beliveher
#metooindia #writersofinstagram

the  movement, like i said earlier, is a fight against systematic patriarchal constructs that make us scared everyday. think about it this way: it is about any violence committed where the imbalance in the cultural and societal powers of the genders play a role. an abusive man hitting a woman believes he is superior to her, which is why he has the authority to do what he does. the boss situation is even more messed up, because first of all, he sees his employee as consumable because of her femininity, and because here, the employee-boss power structure plays an additional role. there can be no sure consent in a relationship with such a tainted balance scale of power. in the boss-employee dynamic, it is institutional power. in the abuser-abused dynamic, it is psychological.
.
.
.
 why do anonymous accounts hold credibility at all? 
because of you. because you make life living hell for women who gather the courage after an intense amount of work and name someone. because sometimes, there is still a power imbalance and the women does not feel secure enough to speak up, but still wants to, to prevent future possible victims- and bring to light who the man really is.
.
.
.

 oh. i just realized i have been wrong about everything. i am so sorry. what can i do to help?

suppo the survivors. point out when someone around you objectifies, boasts about, or harasses a woman. sta having higher standards for what kind of people you want to associate with. do not pass off things as locker room talk or 'boys will be boys'. answer all these questions for whoever is the next person to even casually discuss them them with you. but most impoantly, once again, suppo the survivors. and promise to help build a place where they would not be any.
 eliveher

today has been an extremely overwhelming day for me! i shared a story of my experiences. good bad and ugly all of it and i agree i was at fault too in my choices and decisions. today it has given me the strength to be who i am and the people i choose to keep in my life. it's not easy for anyone and i know that. i changed for myself and my sanity. thankfully women and men are opening up and speaking fearlessly. for those who stood by me and for those who taught me the lessons. i'm grateful to all! 
thank you @mumbaigirl14 @thetimesofindia for being such a wonderful friend who heard me without judgement and gave me the opportunity to share my story. @bombaytimes

this poem is relevant to me more than ever now. "where the mind is without fear and the head is held high
where knowledge is free
where the world has not been broken up into fragments
by narrow domestic walls
where words come out from the depth of truth
where tireless striving stretches its arms towards perfection
where the clear stream of reason has not lost its way
into the dreary desert sand of dead habit
where the mind is led forward by thee
into ever-widening thought and action
into that heaven of freedom, my father, let my country awake."
- rabindranath tagore

text:
since the #metoo movement began, there have been countless feature articles in the media about the endurance, persistence, strength and ability of women. as a photographer, i get so excited to see the incredible portraits of these amazing, empowered women‚Ä¶ until i look at the photo credit and (heart sink) realize it was shot by a man.

in fact, less than 8% of all advertising and media imagery is created by women, even though women account for a whopping 85% of consumer spending.

don‚Äôt get me wrong. male photographers are great. but don‚Äôt you think that more, a lot more, of the imagery shot for stories about women, or to sell stuff to women, should be shot through the eyes of a woman? maybe i‚Äôm biased, but i do.

that's why i‚Äôm honoured and proud to be part of @alreadymadeorg , a directory of women photographers, directors and branded image creators, founded by photographer @jill.greenberg .

#thefemalelens #diversifythelens #womenempoweringwomen #photography #advertising #womenphotographer #genderparity #alreadymade

text:
#metoo (part 2/4 of answering questions whose existence has convinced me that i'm never going to be able to speak up. to read the entire list in one go, please click on the link in my bio.) .
.
#3: that's okay, but #notallmen.

thank you for informing us. we'll remember this the next time our heart beats faster when we're alone in a lift with four men. or we are asked to wear longer clothes because we might 'provoke' you. the point is #yesallwomen. and we know that there are good men out there. but if at this moment, you are using your hashtags to prove that you are one of them instead of supporting the victims, you're really not. nobody has called out for a mass shooting of men. unless you identify with the assaulters, i don't see the problem.
.
.

#4: acha, okay. if i can't say #notallmen, i can say #himtoo, right? men get assaulted too, you know.

yes, i know. and that's a problem. and we need to change it. but firstly, how could you have possibly found a gendered word in the phrase 'me too', to feel a need to create a counter hashtag? the existence of #himtoo, implies that #metoo comes with an understanding that there are no male victims. which is exactly what the people who want to bring down the movement want to do: portray it as a fight against the genuineness of male victims, rather than the fight against systematic patriarchal constructs that make women scared everyday. i understand that there are male victims, but men don't continuously feel a need to take precautions like which streets to avoid to not get raped, and continuously watch my drink to not get raped, and carry a pepper spray to not get raped, like women do. there is a difference.

picture by: @raunak_makhija
#feminism #metooindia #writersofinstagram #believeher

thank you for informing us. we'll remember this the next time our heart beats faster when we're alone in a lift with four men. or we are asked to wear longer clothes because we might 'provoke' you. the point is #yesallwomen. and we know that there are good men out there. but if at this moment, you are using your hashtags to prove that you are one of them instead of supporting the victims, you are really not. nobody has called out for a mass shooting of men. unless you identify with the assaulters, i do not see the problem.
.
.

#4: acha, okay. if i can not say #notallmen, i can say #himtoo, right? men get assaulted too, you know.

yes, i know. and that's a problem. and we need to change it. but firstly, how could you have possibly found a gendered word in the phrase 'me too', to feel a need to create a counter hashtag? the existence of #himtoo, implies that #metoo comes with an understanding that there are no male victims. which is exactly what the people who want to bring down the movement want to do: portray it as a fight against the genuineness of male victims, rather than the fight against systematic patriarchal constructs that make women scared everyday. i understand that there are male victims, but men do not continuously feel a need to take precautions like which streets to avoid to not get raped, and continuously watch my drink to not get raped, and carry a pepper spray to not get raped, like women do. there is a difference.

text:
i have been really sick. it started the day of  october  5th. sudden excruciating pelvic pain. worse than when my gallbladder burst years ago. i couldn't even crawl to my phone. i thought i may die from whatever was causing the pain. after 2.5 hours of screaming on the floor i was able to get to my cellphone and make a call for help.
this was my first pelvic pain related visit to the emergency room, at my age and with the chronic pain it surprises me how bad it had to be for me to go to the hospital.  they saw large burst cyst leaking into me and said the only thing that  helps is time. i heard needle biopsy from someone but when i followed up nobody seemed like it was necessary.
2 weeks later with little to no relief for the pain, hot baths and heat pads were all i had. the pelvic pain clinic that was referred to me by  the dr who was referred to me by my surgeon turned me away, and said they wouldn't even take a self pay patient.  i had been to that clinic in the passed, they gave my initial diagnosis of the big fibroid. the 8 months of bleeding golf ball clots and having no unstained panties, sheets, towels, pants, shorts.  i remember a little about that life. now it continues.  a 6 month process of referrals and waiting and and anxiety phone calls and pointless appointments ending with being turned away by the very waters that forced me there.
but i digress, seriously.  2 weeks later i fainted getting out of the bath. i'll talk about it in my next post.
#endometriosis #endowarrior #endofailure #pcos #adenomyosis #interstitialcystitis #chronicillness #chronicpain #migraine #chronicheadache #lookingforallies #antibullying #livinginpain #humanrights #medicalcoverage #discriminatory #disability #depression #anxiety #majordepressivedisorder #metoo #trauma #ptsd #nightmares #insomnia #nightterrors

text:
i invite you to contribute your thoughts and creativity to a live collaborative art project entitled, ‚Äú#metoo - moving from pain to power‚Äù in my art studio on the second floor of avenue arts marketplace and theatre. join me in creating an artistic dialog about the impact of sexual violence against women in our society during canton first friday multicultural canton. üé®
for years, an inordinate number of women have experienced sexual violence and harassment, yet they have felt compelled to bear their pain in silence and solitude. indeed, most have us have accepted our vulnerability to sexual violence and harassment as a part of being a woman, and when it actually happened to us, we bore it with resignation, shame and stoic silence.
üé®
but something has changed. when a man who bragged about sexually exploiting women was elected as president of the united states, women began to say, "no more!"
üé®
with the advent of the #metoo movement, women have been sharing their stories of pain, and they have been refusing to remain silent as they have in the past.
üé®
so where does this go? there is great power in the sharing of stories, but that alone will not change the power structures in society that support male dominance and violence towardsdd women. how do women move beyond the pain and towards the kind of power that can change the dynamics that feed sexual violence?
üé®
i would like to capture a dialog about different thoughts and ideas on these issues in "dialogues mural". you can contribute simply by joining the conversation. (visit: http://bztatstudios.com/art-services/dialogues-murals/ to learn about dialogues murals.)
üé®
i will begin this process in a live collaborative event during the canton first friday multicultural canton on november 2, 2018. it won't end there, however. i will also make some opportunities for you to contribute your thoughts online if you aren't able to make it to canton. stay tuned.
üé®
all creative contributions will be anonymous yet each voice will be artistically amplified. voices shared can be those of survivors, allies, and persons of any gender or gender identity.
üé®
i thank you for considering being a part of the dialog.

text:
it‚Äôs halloween.. have you gotten in touch with your inner bitch witch yet? if not, andi zeisler (https://www.bitchmedia.org/article/its-time-embrace-feminisms-anger) tells you why you should: .
.
we‚Äôve spent much of the last two years hearing endlessly about white, male anger. the fury that donald trump‚Äôs base channeled into public hatred of women, black and brown people, and the ‚Äúfake news.‚Äù the entitled resentment that turned the ad hominem trolling of gamergate into a new political strategy egged on by steve bannon and breitbart. the men on twitter and facebook who insult women for sport but run crying to mark zuckerberg when women fight back. the aggrieved, polo-shirted, torch-wielding rage of the neo-nazis who chanted ‚Äújews will not replace us‚Äù in charlottesville, physically attacked an interracial couple, and murdered protester heather heyer.
and yet the targets of this weaponized anger are still regularly encouraged to sympathize with it, take it seriously, expend time and energy to understand it. the fact that white men‚Äôs anger is perhaps the easiest thing in the world to understand‚Äîthey are losing bits and pieces of their power to those over whom they have lorded it for centuries, and they are terrified‚Äîseemed lost on the many, many media outlets that urged readers and viewers to sympathize with racists, homo- and transphobes, and actual nazis.
but while white male anger is born of fear, almost any woman‚Äôs anger provokes it. for most of our lives, female anger is a taboo that, like adjacent no-nos like power and sexual autonomy, is supposed to be kept tightly under wraps lest it spring open like some sort of jack-in-the-box medusa. the fear of a woman‚Äôs anger is just one facet of a larger fear of women breaking the normative bonds of social control, of shirking their duties as peacekeepers and boat-righters to put themselves first. in short, it is terrifying, particularly to men, and so the history of women‚Äôs anger goes hand-in-hand with a history of oppression. angry women were tried and burned as witches and fitted with contraptions that literally silenced them. they were hustled off to sanitariums, medicated into submission, and gas

text:
we know you guys are paying attention to the midterms - ping is down in texas to see what all the fuss with @betoorourke is about. and boy is this one divided state. texas hasn't gone blue since 1935, so there shouldn't be a hope in hell that beto can win....and yet the new york times has him down by only 7 points. it appears to be so close that ted cruz had to call in papa president, donald trump, to come do a rally to shore up some support. in texas of all places, i mean this is the land of oil, guns and republicans...or so we thought?

all of this anger is resulting in higher youth voter turnout‚Ä¶ the age bracket most likely to vote for a young liberal guy touting universal healthcare and legalization of cannabis

we've seen beto in action. we've knocked on some doors. got yelled at by some less than friendly republicans. but at the end of the day, we still think texas will remain red.

text: one year ago today i sat down in my living room, propped my phone up on my coffee table, and recorded a video. i spoke about being a survivor of sexual assault - and about it gets better. how if you‚Äôve gone through something similar, i promise, even if you don‚Äôt feel it or can‚Äôt believe me now, that life gets beautiful again and is worth fighting to hold onto. i was terrified to post it...but i did. one year later, i have made over one hundred and fifty videos about life after trauma. i could never have predicted a year ago what that video would launch for me internally...the amount of healing i‚Äôve found by telling my story, putting things into words, and connecting with so many amazing fellow survivors and supporters of survivors all over the world is unmeasurable. i am so, so grateful for each and every one of you who has supported me and been a part of this. i have no plans to stop, and am so excited for what the future holds. üòä i love you all...thank you for this past year! üíú

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

in the wake of the #metoo movement, #sexualassault has been a frequently discussed topic in recent months. the growing awareness of the problem has helped to bring many cases out of the dark, and encouraged #survivors to bring charges against their #abusers. it is important for #victims of sexual assault to get the help they need to heal and recover. it is also vital that they understand their rights and how to obtain help if they decide to take #legal action against the perpetrator.

sexual assaults can have devastating effects on victims, including both physical harm and mental and emotional #trauma. these attacks are never something to take lightly or to sweep under the rug. it is a terrible situation to be faced with, and it can leave victims feeling alone, afraid, and unsure of what to do.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text: this past weekend, i co-hosted the annual united nations young changemakers conclave. the last six months of planning it almost made me feel like i was back in college, doing what i always loved: being a part of a large group, and taking time to gather, discuss and jointly problem solve. today, in the light of important movements such as #metoo, and the increasing incidences of women braving the spotlight with their truths‚Äîrisking career, reputation, privacy & piece of mind‚Äîwe are constantly reminded of the importance and the need to speak up. to talk to each other‚Äîto communicate. and the unycc is a platform that highlights and emphasises the importance of just that, as well as some of the great initiatives that are surfacing or are already in place in india today. in the coming months we will continue the discussion through @wacindia - reimagining things like motherhood, career, marriage, sexuality, happiness and self-esteem. thank you to all our partners and volunteers who made the event possible. thanks to @toliapooja for working day and night to make it happen. and thank you @samyakc, for choosing me as your co-president this year. thank you thank you thank you üôèüèΩ #unycc #unitednations #unycc2018 #ycc2018 #india #reimagine #usconsulate #xbillionlabs #wacindia #impact #event

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the start.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing for the 2016 election.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the content and more or less fake accounts - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking the responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole thing is build on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason.

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
google walkout: employees stage protest over handling of sexual harassment, #nyc

employees at google offices around the world held a wave of walkouts on thursday to protest the company‚Äôs handling of sexual harassment.
the walkouts, which started in asia and spread across continents, were planned for around 11 a.m. in their time zones. protests were expected through the day in google offices in the united states.

the backlash was prompted by an article in the new york times last week that revealed that google had paid millions of dollars in exit packages to male executives accused of harassment, while staying silent about the transgressions.

text_retweet:
#repost  @earthlove777 rp @rod_veg_yves rp @gnarbivore rp @gnarbivore: "what's so bad about eggs?
üê£
the egg industry is one of the most inherently cruel of those in today's world of animal exploitation.
.
layer hens are kept in decrepit conditions, regardless of whether the carton states free range or organic! an inability to fluff and groom their feathers, extend their wings, scratch and graze and socialise drive the poor animals insane.
.
layer hens are selectively bred, genetically modified and manipulated into laying an unnatural amount of eggs compared to what they would naturally.
.
male chicks cannot lay eggs and are therefore considered a waste product. they are stuffed into plastic bags where they are left to suffocate or they are dropped into a macerator alive and turned into a pink pulp.
.
not to mention they are full of cholesterol and carcinogens!
. 
don't directly contribute to the murder and severe mistreatment of these poor, innocent beings. boycott eggs. be vegan. make the world a better place to live for all species that share the planet with us!

text:
recept om te falen in de liefde 
op verzoek deel ik deze openbaar, maar het voelt wel super kwetsbaar. ik schreef dit recept in een oefening tijdens de womb wisdom retreat bij yama voorhorst. 
de oefening hielp heel erg om met humor naar grote thema's te kijken. de humor maakt het makkelijker om zelf verantwoordelijkheid te nemen voor het zootje wat we er vaak van maken in ons leven. 
letterlijk alles wat in onze realiteit verschijnt is onze eigen creatie. hoe pijnlijk die confrontatie ook is, als we dat echt gaan zien en voelen, kunnen we ons vrij maken van deze gevangenis. sommige pijnlijke situaties overkomen ons inderdaad, maar het clich√© is waar: wij kunnen kiezen hoe we ermee omgaan. 
dit recept is ook weer een stapje in het 'ownen' van mijn shit in mijn liefdesleven. en het is een begin van mijn excuses aan de mannen in mijn leven. 
komt ie dan.. mijn recept om zeer ongelukkig te worden in de liefde ;-) "kies een partner waarvan je van te voren al weet dat het heel ingewikkeld gaat worden. iemand met onverwerkte trauma's bijvoorbeeld, die dat lekker afreageert op de buitenwereld. als iemand af en toe behoorlijk depressief is, des te beter. 
probeer hem dan te redden van zijn misere. focus al je aandacht op hem. geef jezelf totaal weg. verzin verhalen over hem die hem zwart maken, zodat jij hem kunt redden. als je geen verhaal weet, dan staan er online leuke artikelen over narcisme. maak jezelf tot slachtoffer. geef hem vervolgens de schuld van alles. veroordeel hem om alles wat hij fout doet. sluit jezelf compleet af om liefde te ontvangen en verwijt hem dat hij je geen liefde geeft.

ondertussen heb je wel gewoon seks met hem. laat hem ook daarin goed voelen dat hij niet goed genoeg is, zodat jij hem kunt redden. plaats jezelf ver boven hem als wijze tantrika, zodat hij je hart nooit kan raken. sluit je hart en je yoni voor hem af. vertrouw hem niet, maar laat hem wel met je vrijen. dit zorgt voor een goede dosis pijn in je yoni, waar je hem vervolgens de schuld van kunt geven. onthoud: hij is de gemene narcist en jij bent het slachtoffer. als je per ongeluk toch je aandacht op jezelf richt, duik dan dieper in het slachtofferschap. >>>

text:
a hard journey !!!
.
its all so hard,its so difficult, will i be able to do it?? i am working hard, but then why is it not happening..?? am i doing something wrong,am i not good with my pictures?? all this going on my mind since lasy 2 days and believe me,i know whys and hows of all these question yet, i don't want to accept it that its me who has to work it out,its me who has to decide upon the content, its me who has to sit and edit for hours those videos which i shot almost 6 months back, its me who has to shoot those video ideas written on my diary and planners, its me who has to be consistent with my uploads but its me who is not ready to accept that its a hard journey, and i have to walk on it... .

text_retweet:
#repost from @crossover_studios with @regram.app ... part i 
today i got a wake up call,
i was shocked still but ignored it all,
i opened the door and walked away,
while like me others they slay,
i ran with all i had,
i stopped to take a breathe i was sad,
i was angry,
with all tom, dicks & harry,
i cried my lungs out
touched a few decibels 
no humans though
there has to be a way to take out this anger,
this frustration,
this feeling sorry,
this going mad,

so here is to victims of power
victims of comments that shower,
india will rise again,
to the ones who should be shamed,
to whose manipulations we are aimed,
i will not loose again,
to the couches & fame,
unbottle the bottled feelings,
i am for me too 
are you? ......

text:
let's talk election day, friends.
‚Ä¢
there has been a huge push to register to vote, go out to vote, and engage in politics.
‚Ä¢
but activism doesn't end on november 6th. it can't end on election day. there is still so much work to do.
‚Ä¢
and change doesn't always happen at the top. we have an obligation  to continuously show up for ourselves and the more marginalized.
‚Ä¢
complacency is dangerous.
‚Ä¢
[image description: "when does your activism end?"]
‚Ä¢

text:
episode 91 is up! when we read dorothy carvello‚Äòs memoir anything for a hit: an a&r woman‚Äôs story of surviving the music industry we were blown away. dorothy had a life-long dream of working in the music industry and when the opportunity arose to work for atlantic records president ahmet ertegun, dorothy jumped at the chance. almost immediately she would discover this was no regular workplace. as dorothy put it ‚Äúif personnel had actually enforced the rules, everyone in the building would have been fired by lunch.‚Äù
with dorothy‚Äôs dream job came amazing highs and very low lows.  sexual harassment and rampant drug use were all common daily occurrences and dorothy battled constant misogyny with every step. nevertheless she excelled, working her way up from ahmet‚Äôs secretary to atlantic records first female a&r executive. dorothy loved going to live shows and the thrill of discovering and nurturing untapped talent but the constant abuse, both mental and physical from her male co-workers certainly took it‚Äôs toll.
dorothy would fight back and to this day continues to do so.  we recently had a riveting conversation with dorothy about how she pushed past the societal expectations she was raised with and how she built her career in the music industry. we also discussed her very unique friendship with ahmet and couldn‚Äôt help but ask about the beautiful man named michael hutchence who was a shining example of what a man could be among the toxic masculinity. we talk about how we need to continue to push forward with #timesup and #metoo because the battle isn‚Äôt over but thankfully there are women like dorothy who are putting these stories forward and fighting back. everyone needs to pick up a copy of this book immediately! listen on our site (link in bio!) & itunes. make sure to also check out our network @rnrarchaeology for more amazing podcasts! ‚ô°

text: op het rembrandtplein in amsterdam is vanmiddag seks, macht & misbruik van journalist frank waals gepresenteerd. het boek verschijnt twee dagen nadat het openbaar ministerie voormalig castingdirector job gosschalk opriep voor verhoor n.a.v. een aangifte en melding. de officier van justitie is voornemens nog dit jaar te bepalen of de aanklachten daadwerkelijk tot een zaak leiden. tijdens de presentatie spraken diverse ingewijden uit de tv- en theaterwereld, waaronder choreograaf barrie stevens. hij gaf aan het als directeur op de fontys hogeschool tilburg soms lastig te hebben gevonden verleidingen op zijn pad te hebben gekregen, maar deze wel altijd te hebben kunnen weerstaan. actrice inge ipenburg hield een vlammend betoog over het huidige klimaat in acteerland. 'ik heb al vijf jaar geen screentest gedaan en ben bereid schoenzolen te likken om gewoon in aanmerking te komen voor √©√©n van die tientallen rollen waarvoor ik gezien mijn leeftijd en capaciteiten geschikt zou zijn (...) er moet een oplossing komen voor de angst en zwijgcultuur die er onder acteurs hangt. de kans op rollen ligt nog steeds in handen van een kleine, machtige organisatie met praktische alleenheerschappij. dat was de situatie waar #metoo vandaan komt. en dat is de situatie nog steeds.' in het boek komen psychologen en hersendeskundigen aan het woord die verklaren waarom misdadigers doen wat ze doen en worden verhalen en cijfers uit andere branches, zoals de zorg, horeca en sport, gepresenteerd. in nederland zegt 15% van de mannen en 24% van de vrouwen slachtoffer te zijn geworden door intimidatie. #persbericht #nieuws #boek @frankwaals #metoo #lancering #amsterdam #cijfers @ingeipenburg #barrystevens #entertainmentnews #nieuws @royalpromotions_nl @marcodekoning #nieuwsmakers #press #media #instamedia

text:
i know it takes immense courage to just accept that we have been molested leave alone to tell the world our story.
our bodies are memory maps and when our bodies get physically violated against our will, a black spot is created on the map and it takes a lot of time for that spot to fade away. and sadly, it is not just time. it takes a lot of effort on our part and a good support system to acknowledge such traumas, be mentally unaffected and move on with life.
and in most cases the perpetrators run free, unscathed, while we carry our emotional baggages and keep acting like nothing happened. and when the molester is a family member, friend or a senior at workplace, the emotional torture just goes to another level.
i know because i have been molested not once but multiple times. by strangers, by a cousin, by a friend. i have been subjected to horrendous bodily violation over and over again. and i believe 99.9% indian women are subjected to such physical violations in their lifetime. sometimes it takes a lot of time to even acknowledge the fact that we have been molested because our body goes into complete shock.
to all those men and women who are speaking vile about the #metoo movement, i just have one thing to say. "either you are a molester yourself or you have never been molested."
i feel especially sorry for the women who are saying stupid things about other women who are being brave enough to stand up for themselves. really, if you spit in the air it will land on your face, remember?
to all the women who are speaking up, please don't stop. it takes a lot of courage to come this far. hold your ground. stand strong. more #power to you.
#strongwomen #womenempowerment #bosslady #femaleempowerment #womensupportingwomen #zivamesquad

text: last week i went to a powerful film screening of amae, thamee, ama ( mother, daughter, sister), which exposes the burmese military's practice of using rape as a weapon of war and gave voice to kachin and rohingya women activists calling for justice for these crimes. we heard powerful and heart wrenching testimonies from survivors, witnesses, and activists about the sexual violence and their impact on women and their communities that brought me to tears. during this time of the #metoo movement, it's important to be aware that it doesn't just end at our borders but extends far beyond to countries that have even less avenues to pursue justice against these crimes. it's time to raise awareness and really think about the solutions that will bring long term change. let's not have this be "old news". #hertoo #metoomovement #justiceforrohingya #throwbackthursday #gwesia #sigurcenterforasianstudies #genderequalityinitiative

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
#metoo movement | ojaswi harlalka |

after a year of headlines, #metoo is everywhere. it has left a scathing mark worldwide. twitter is exploding with allegations of sexual harassment and everyone around the globe is expressing their anxiety and dismay.

the fair sex is sharing their harassment cases in every field - journalism, film industry, workplace, politics and the list follows. some men won't change and will never respect a woman's dignity and would never stop treating them as their sex objects.
(don't call me a womanist, for i don't mean all men, i'm just raising my voice against the assaulters.)
.
we always have a misconception that being an actress, or specifically living a movie star's life is easy. have you ever heard of the 'casting couch', the main and the most traumatic ingredient of the film industry - where female debutants are asked to seduce their directors, to grab a role in the movies? nevertheless, journalism offers you the same. also, how to forget the adventurous air-hostess profession, where juniors are asked to sleep with senior pilots and ground staffs to get a promotion?
.
and even after such behaviour, 'we' choose to keep quiet, suffer in this manner but never take a stand for ourselves. why? because 'chaar logon ke saamne hamari aur hamare parivar ki bezzati ho jaaegi'. our majestic supreme court strikes down #section377 and #section497, but with the rising stack of case files, there is an alarming need to criminalize these unorthodox practices. we just don't need an order stating, 'death penalty for rapes under the pocso act', but we need real actions against it.

you can rationalise by saying: "no girl will feel good seeing her father, brother or uncle hanging to death in front of their eyes.", but you have never asked those fathers, brothers or uncles if they even feel anything while treating others' daughters or sisters with such disgrace.
i am not taking sides of the projected victims. i don't know their full story. but if it's true, then please stop defending the culprits.

defending men is easy, taking action against them is tough, and that's where our country is failing to overcome the shameful crimes.

.
.
this work is being continued by this week's guest, @hayleyleibson, founder of @ladyintech and weekly contributor at @forbes via her superb column, who is working tirelessly to improve gender and racial diversity in the tech industry through her platform and her writing. we had a frank discussion about power imbalance, gender diversity, #metoo and why equality in start-ups is vital from the get-go. join us on sunday!
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

i always hated the myth of medusa. she was so beautiful posiden couldn't help but want her. she turned him down and he refused to accept it. she flees to athena's temple and is raped there. athena only appears after and blames medusa. she morphs her into a gorgon that turns men to stone when they look upon her and exiled her to a solitary existence on an island. later athena would then send perseus to slaughter her to kill the monster set to kill andromeda. in this day and age of rape culture in america she is someone i feel drawn to. i am a rape surviver. i escaped being raped at 6 and 14 by two different men. at 21 i was raped by a friend that got me drunk and i never reported it because i froze and didn't say no. vote women. vote out those that think rape is okay.

text:
[warning...long post, but oh so good!] slavery ends here. and it starts with us.

november marks the month of giving. in our efforts
to take a stand and make a global impact, we are eagerly giving a portion of our yearly profits from the sales of our men's cards line towards the @a21 campaign. 
we wanted to share a little tid bit from their website because it really tells the full story of the cause.
------------------------------------------------------------------- slavery is the fastest growing organized crime in the world.

it‚Äôs real, hidden in plain sight, and tearing at the social fabric of every nation and economic structure.

the 21st century abolitionists determined to bring change.

the heart of the organization is to reach, rescue, and restore.

reach¬†- reducing vulnerability

we prevent slavery from ever happening by engaging people through events, student presentations, and education programs.

rescue¬†- identifying victims

we work closely with law enforcement on the ground to support police operations, identify victims through our hotlines, assist in the prosecution of traffickers, represent survivors in court proceedings, and collaborate with governments and other ngos to eradicate slavery at every level.

restore¬†- empowering survivors

we work face-to-face with every person in our care based on their individual needs, providing them with access to housing, medical treatment, counseling, education, employment, and repatriation to help them reach a place of independence.
------------------------------------------------------------------- the #metoo movement has impacted our society in so many ways. we wanted to take a stand in a way that empowered the good men in our lives and really make an impact on women, men and children who truly aren't free.

join is in our campaign to end human trafficking!
to learn more about the a21 campaign please visit their website listed in the comments below.

#metoo #metoomovement #cardsthatmakeadifference #takeastand #giveback #endhumantrafficking #stationeryshop #greetingcards #mensgreetingscards #mensline #menslinecollection #paperbaristas #a21 #a21campaign

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text: developing a close intimate personal relationship with god as my father helped me heal wounds that i didn‚Äôt even realize i had for years.  we all need love, safety and a sense of belonging and when those needs do not get met, we find (unconsciously even) ways to meet those needs short term only to feel lonely and unloved again.  turning to god and really spending time with him really allowed me to feel safe and loved long term which paved the way for a much healthier fulfilling lifetime relationship with my now husband.  i never thought i‚Äôd have a 10 year anniversary but today marks 10 amazing years with the man of my dreams!  there‚Äôs a huge difference between knowledge and experience and today i encourage everyone to intentionally foster a relationship with god so you can feel loved, safe, worthy and connected. #theemptiedheart #healingfromabuse #childabusesurvivor #sexabusesurvivor #sexualabuse #abbafather #abba #godismyfather #metoo #metoomovement #stopthecycle #womeninspiringwomen #turntogod #lookup #lookupchild #lookupchildtour

i am counting down the hours until i stand as the key note speaker for the media hub event in cookham at the bel & dragon. the media hub is one of my favourite events, i have built solid working relationships from here and love the energy you receive from that one evening.

tonight, i will be sharing my story through life and the reason i wrote don't hold back. have you read my book? if so would you be kind enough to write your review on amazon, thank you. 
so, i will sign off now and calm my nerves ahead of tonight, i look forward to seeing those that have booked in and for anyone else who is stuck to know what to do tonight, then think no more, i would love to see you tonight and introduce you to my media friends in cookham!

you will love it!! come along..... for tickets please follow the eventbrite link https://www.eventbrite.co.uk/e/the-media-hub-with-author-emma-jane-taylor-tickets-50824598743?aff=ebdssbdestsearch&utm-medium=discovery&utm-campaign=social&utm-content=attendeeshare&utm-source=cp&utm-term=destsearch

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
i wrote something in light of the #metoo movement.// unrest-

your nana hit you with his wooden stick 
when he caught you trying to jump across your neighbour's wall,
you were six, and rahman, your best friend. 
but nana carried six decades of hurt and betrayal from a border 
his family was forced to cross, 
he wanted to teach you, 
we do not jump over walls,
we do not cross borders, 
if we can do without it.
so you carry your angst within,
you hope the fire of your wrath would be burnt down by meaningless sex, 
so you drag her into bed, 
you know you are crossing lines,
expanding your territory, 
but nana has been dead for over two decades, 
and if she's quiet, she must want to be taken over, too,
just like nana's home, 
in another land, another time.
the first time we met,
there was so much fire in your eyes, 
one could easily misread desire for passion. 
i wanted to rest, it was a tiring day at work, 
you wanted to make love, 
you told me the opposite of rest is unrest,
how we need it now more than ever.
we need unrest in our streets, under the sheets and everywhere else, 
it's time, you say, to take back what's rightfully ours.
it's been five years you're gone,
you fight in foreign lands,
losing battles the same way i did to you.
nana must be weeping to see you cross all the borders he asked you not to.
you must fight for your land,
i must fight for mine,
you were right, your time is up, 
this is our biggest unrest,
give me back what's rightfully mine.

@purba_barua by @vieenrozz

text:
dear good guys,
i know you‚Äôre out there because i am fortunate enough to share my life with many of you. however, unfortunately most men still think of women as creatures to be controlled, oppressed and abused, simply because we‚Äôre created differently.
today, 52% of the world‚Äôs population is female, yet most powerful and prestigious positions are occupied by men. women are paid less than their male counterparts, and harassed and exploited at the workplace, which btw, is way more rampant than you believe.
it takes immense courage for a woman to talk about it openly, as the repercussions are brutal, especially in a society where the blame for all wrong is pinned on to the woman. she is inherently and eternally guilty. if she‚Äôs raped, she‚Äôs brought it upon herself. if she‚Äôs beaten by her husband it‚Äôs because she‚Äôs not performing her duties well. if she‚Äôs in a love with a married man, she is the homewrecker, while the man cheating on his family is blameless.
girls are raised being told how to behave, dress, walk, talk, eat, drink and even think. as a man, can you imagine living like that?
you cannot fathom how scary it is to be objectified, bullied, controlled and violated ‚Äì to be shockingly visible and invisible at the same time. we don‚Äôt want  to dominate the world, or men, for that matter. all we want is respect, dignity and equality in our personal and professional lives.
but we can‚Äôt  do this by ourselves. we need you to influence the minds of other men, because you are our best bet. we need men to start the conversation. we need men to not look away. speak up for the other half of the planet, because all it takes for evil to triumph is for good men to do nothing.
- bindiya murgai @healinghideaway_bindiyamurgai
.

text:
cheekhti khamoshi!

yet another campaign from the #metoo series. the women depicted in the pictures are not just mere characters, they are every woman who has at some point in her life fallen prey to the heinous act of harassment; who is exploited everyday by the hands of this misogynist society where they tell her to be quiet. kyun kay izzat ka mamla hai, loag kya kehengay? 
let's all say no to #harassment, stand up for ourselves, our sisters, friends, our acquaintances and each and every woman in our society who deserves so much more than being hushed for her vulnerability. let's help each other rise and stand tall against the twisted standard of morality that prevails in our society. 
i am highly grateful to sheema kermani for providing me with a platform to express my thoughts through my art - makeup! for their women‚Äôs peace table on sexual harassment organised by tehreek-e-niswan held at the arts council karachi.

cheekhti khamoshi!

yet another campaign from the #metoo series. the women depicted in the pictures are not just mere characters, they are every woman who has at some point in her life fallen prey to the heinous act of harassment; who is exploited everyday by the hands of this misogynist society where they tell her to be quiet. kyun kay izzat ka mamla hai, loag kya kehengay? 
let's all say no to #harassment, stand up for ourselves, our sisters, friends, our acquaintances and each and every woman in our society who deserves so much more than being hushed for her vulnerability. let's help each other rise and stand tall against the twisted standard of morality that prevails in our society. 
i am highly grateful to sheema kermani for providing me with a platform to express my thoughts through my art - makeup! for their women‚Äôs peace table on sexual harassment organised by tehreek-e-niswan held at the arts council karachi.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text: i have to give it to my mom @pamelaforncrook because whenever lili doesn‚Äôt want to give her a hug and kiss goodbye, my mom always says, that‚Äôs fine i don‚Äôt want her to if she doesn‚Äôt want to.  i thought to myself today, i‚Äôve been bribing lili sometimes to give hugs and kisses to our loved ones, but is that right?? with the larger #metoo movement going on, it‚Äôs made me think more about how our social experiences as littles form us and what we understand as acceptable behavior as well as our understanding of words.  as a parent, i am constantly re-evaluating and trying to provide the healthiest environment for my daughter so that she knows she‚Äôs powerful and has rights and a voice.  now that lili is vocalizing her feelings - she knows how to say no and how to say yes, but she‚Äôs still learning learning the function and boundaries of yes and no and how can i help her in this process?  what goes on when she‚Äôs an adult starts here.  am i teaching her that her feelings are undervalued by bribing her to give hugs and kisses when she really doesn‚Äôt want to, yes and it stops now.  i have family members that kiss and hug or tickle lili in affection and she says no or stop sometimes and they sometimes keep going because ‚Äúthey‚Äù think she is getting pure love and it‚Äôs good for her.  are they teaching her that her ‚Äúno‚Äù is not valued and someone else knows what she needs better, yes and it stops here!  it starts here people!!! let‚Äôs start the conversation now and teach our littles that value of no or stop and that words have meaning and that when they express them, they‚Äôre heard, acknowledged, understood,  valued, and respected.  i know i‚Äôll start it now and hope you will too! (fyi - not saying that anytime your kid says no to stop in your tracks, we have to parent, but rather respect your littles emotional and physical boundaries while helping and encouraging them to love and be respectful little people cause they grow up to be us...adults, and what they learn as littles forms their character as adults). #metoo #itstartshere #baby #toddler #love #respect #learn #grow

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
we've been told for too long <<< smile <<< stay quiet <<< look pretty <<< follow what everyone else is dong,
while simultaneously squashing a voice deep inside of us. but if we listen to it... that voice gets louder. <><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>
what do you think when you see others mistreated?
how do you feel following the crowd out of convenience?
when will you be ready to say out loud,
>>> that's not true.
>>> i believe her.
>>> no more. never again.
<><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><><>

text:
leading ladies of indian armed forces. üáÆüá≥üáÆüá≥üáÆüá≥ on one side of border, you can spot burkha or hijab clad women while on other side ladies leading from front. that is is the beauty of india. we don't need a fake and sick #metoo movement of accusations and allegations (most of which are baseless and are done to gain publicity). in our culture, we have been worshiping and giving importance to women empowerment for centuries. 
it's high time rather than creating an unnecessary gender divide, we recognize our culture and live up to it. 
kudos to #crpf for making this statement without any hashtag movement.

- she [rebekah mercer] loved me. she was like, oh we need more of your type on our side!

your type? - the gays. she loved the gays. so did steve [bannon]. he saw us as early adopters. he figured, if you can get the gays on board, everyone else will follow. it‚Äôs why he was so into the whole milo [yiannopoulos] thing.

robert mercer was a pioneer in ai and machine translation. he helped invent algorithmic trading ‚Äì which replaced hedge fund managers with computer programs ‚Äì and he listened to wylie‚Äôs pitch. it was for a new kind of political message-targeting based on an influential and groundbreaking 2014 paper researched at cambridge‚Äôs psychometrics centre, called: - computer-based personality judgments are more accurate than those made by humans. - in politics, the money man is usually the dumbest person in the room. whereas it‚Äôs the opposite way around with mercer, says wylie. - he said very little, but he really listened. he wanted to understand the science. and he wanted proof that it worked.

carole cadwalladr

text:
- she [rebekah mercer] loved me. she was like, oh we need more of your type on our side!

your type? - the gays. she loved the gays. so did steve [bannon]. he saw us as early adopters. he figured, if you can get the gays on board, everyone else will follow. it‚Äôs why he was so into the whole milo [yiannopoulos] thing.

robert mercer was a pioneer in ai and machine translation. he helped invent algorithmic trading ‚Äì which replaced hedge fund managers with computer programs ‚Äì and he listened to wylie‚Äôs pitch. it was for a new kind of political message-targeting based on an influential and groundbreaking 2014 paper researched at cambridge‚Äôs psychometrics centre, called: - computer-based personality judgments are more accurate than those made by humans. - in politics, the money man is usually the dumbest person in the room. whereas it‚Äôs the opposite way around with mercer, says wylie. - he said very little, but he really listened. he wanted to understand the science. and he wanted proof that it worked.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
q: how should i respond when someone tells me they‚Äôve been sexually assaulted? .
.
this is the question that came to me in a text this week. it‚Äôs a legit question.  it‚Äôs not easy to respond. but this question right here- is the best way you can respond. .
.
this allows you to put the power back in the survivors corner. in a situation where they felt powerless- you validate their power and allow them to make a choice. .
.
arm yourself with empathy, resources, and focus on the power you can give back to a survivor. remind them it‚Äôs not their fault- and ask them how you can support them. it can be the catalyst to allowing them to heal. .
.

text:
whenever i heard someone telling their ghastly tales, i would utter a #metoo just loud enough only for my ears to hear. 
whenever i heard someone crying and weeping, i would utter a #metoo just loud enough only for my ears to hear. 
whenever i heard someone unable to speak up because what they had gone through was too much for them to bear, i would utter a #metoo just loud enough only for my ears to hear.

whenever i saw someone mark themselves with the sharp edges of a knife because the pain was just too much for them to hold in, i would utter a #metoo just loud enough only for my ears to hear. whenever i saw someone talk about their experiences i would assume, oh it must be a female. clasping fate in her two brutally cut hands.  until i heard someone, only to look back and realise, the same two eyes, the same two hands, the same two ears, divided only by our biological distinction utter the same two words as me.

text:
today has been an extremely overwhelming day for me! i shared a story of my experiences. good bad and ugly all of it and i agree i was at fault too in my choices and decisions. today it has given me the strength to be who i am and the people i choose to keep in my life. it's not easy for anyone and i know that. i changed for myself and my sanity. thankfully women and men are opening up and speaking fearlessly. for those who stood by me and for those who taught me the lessons. i'm grateful to all! 
thank you @mumbaigirl14 @thetimesofindia for being such a wonderful friend who heard me without judgement and gave me the opportunity to share my story. @bombaytimes

this poem is relevant to me more than ever now. "where the mind is without fear and the head is held high
where knowledge is free
where the world has not been broken up into fragments
by narrow domestic walls
where words come out from the depth of truth
where tireless striving stretches its arms towards perfection
where the clear stream of reason has not lost its way
into the dreary desert sand of dead habit
where the mind is led forward by thee
into ever-widening thought and action
into that heaven of freedom, my father, let my country awake."
- rabindranath tagore

crisis ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî-
according to the u.s. department of health and human services, millions of people in the united states do not receive the mental health care they need. the most common reason for not receiving mental health care is not being able to afford the cost of care. people of color and lgbt individuals are disproportionately impacted by poor access to high-quality affordable mental health care.

many universities, agencies, and nonprofit organizations offer low cost counseling services to individuals and families who do not have access to other affordable options. these services are available to people with or without health insurance. fees are often determined by a sliding scale, where the cost of services is based on your ability to pay.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî-
lowcosthelp.com is national directory of affordable and sliding scale counseling services. access to affordable mental health care should never be limited by your ability to pay.

you can also learn more about the many ways to support survivors of sexual violence
