text:
#kathuarapecase: 'i had to tell even my own brother to disown me,' says deepika singh rajawat

it‚Äôs clear that nothing can cow deepika singh rajawat into silence. the jammu-based lawyer, who is representing the kathua rape victim‚Äôs family, continues to defy threats and intimidation to ensure that justice will finally be served.
besides revealing how she was treated as an outcast by her own community, rajawat, who was in the city to receive the mother teresa memorial award for social justice instituted by harmony foundation, told mirror on the sidelines of the event that the #metoo movement needs to have solid legal support to have any long-term outcomes. she also said the allegations of rape against the activist who led the kathua justice campaign should have no bearing on the kathua case. excerpts from an interview:
what are the challenges you faced when you took up the kathua case?
as a woman lawyer, it was a thrilling and challenging experience. i had to fight people from my own community. many people in jammu criticised and hated me, even going to the extent of saying that i supported an ‚Äúanti-india‚Äù movement. but i did my job sincerely. i was scared for my six-year-old daughter. what helped me through was the realisation that those abusing me were fewer than those supporting me.
why did you take up this controversial case?
people ascribe motives. they think i have a political motive or that i am doing it for money. but i took up this case pro bono. as a law student, there was a subject ‚Äòprofessional ethics‚Äô, which stressed upon a lawyer‚Äôs responsibility outside the court. i am just doing what i am supposed to do as a mother, a lawyer, and most importantly, a woman. i have a daughter who is six years old. it was my moral duty to be there for the kathua victim, regardless of her religion.
how did you deal with threats from the jammu bar association?
they threatened me because i stood up against them. (the bar association had opposed the arrest of the accused and had even allegedly obstructed filing of the chargesheet in court.) the then bar president told me not to appear for the victim‚Äôs family. he even threatened me. but i refused to support the association

how did you deal with threats from the jammu bar association?

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
the wrap‚Äôs power women summit is happening in la and we wish we could be there. this year‚Äôs theme is: the road to 50/50 by 2020. 
offering two days of education, mentorship, workshops and networking, the event promotes the goal of greater women‚Äôs leadership and gender balance in the media, entertainment, and technology industries. ‚ú® counting with the presence of influential women like #metoo movement founder tarana burke, felicity jones, anita hill, alyssa milano, ibtihaj muhammad, emily ratajkowski among others power women summit will also have a music performance by the power trio haim.‚†Ä
the event is also a launchpad and catalyst for concrete measures to help the media and entertainment industry move toward gender equity across the board.üëè
the summit is actively committed to integrating intersectionality in its programming, and to embracing diversity in all possible categories. a significant philanthropic component is integrated into the event through times up and other related non-profits.üíõ
like matriark, wrapwomen provides a platform to accelerate the vision of women who are fighting for a more equitable world. may this be an example for everyone - we support 50/50 by 2020 in all industries! üôå swipe to see some of the confirmed speakers. photos via @elleusa @hollywoodreporter @brandeisuniversity ‚†Ä

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
"most of the shops are using banana leafs and here they're using lotus leaf?"i was curious.
"that's their speciality.try this sri lankan brinjal moju,"my sister passed the dish.
"nice.this reminds me of the sri lankan food that i ate back in hostel.their food always taste different,unlike indian food.infact,it's much delicious,"i shared my thoughts.
"did you saw who is their new pm?"she asked and continued "he has been accused by diplomats of serious human rights abuses in the war against rebel,one of asia's longest-running conflicts that ended during his tenure as president and more than 100,000 people were killed in the 26-year war and yet..,"she stopped.
"do you think it will continue?"
"i doubt it and even if something happen it won't prolong i guess.today's social media game is way too strong,"i told her.
"like the me too stuff?"she questioned.
"yes.sort of.do you think men suddenly became so liberal towards women and allowed them to speak up?"i asked.
"then?"she questioned.
"man are always known for destroying and killing anything that is less powerful than them.they could wipe out the entire woman race with their masculinity but due to their need,they spare them.when the biological needs enter into the psychological mind, that's when  essential need became unnecessary perversion,root of many problem.today a girl can voice out and bring attention to her discrimination solely due to evolution of technology.nothing else."
"other than using technology which clearly never produce much desirable justice,do you think there is a better way?
"wait till elon build a mecha ."
"mecha, what's that?"
"giant fighting and flying human-shaped robot with a pilot onboard.a robot that swings a sword that you can drive it back from work late at night,"i teased but deep inside i know that it's impossible to touch a girl that i see as my people,be it my own sister or a stranger.

text:
#grateful for some constructive criticism i got the other day. it really made me stop & ponder. ultimately led to a realization as to exactly why i let certain situations gain power over me. nice to give myself permission to slow down enough to hear that inner wisdom. 
#perfecttiming 
it's been a long day. 
now to process one of the worst situations someone who calls me a friend, has ever put me in. 
dude tried to lure me into his bed.  it was absolutely disgusting watching a "grown man" attempt to manipulate every weakness i had, including the one he deliberately created.  if it looks like a predator, walks like a predator, talks like a predator..... absolutely disgusting, disturbing behavior. 
this person needs to stop crossing lines with me that never should have been crossed. this boundary is non negotiable

stay in your lane!

#metoo again & again & again..... mad mad world

text:
‚úßcomplex ptsd criteria: part 6‚úß
we're now on the final cptsd criterion and it's a heavy one. "alternations in one's system of meanings" may sound gibberish to many, but we're here to help make it all make sense.
.
the best way to understand this is to think of all the ways prolonged trauma might completely overhaul how one sees the world and all that gives life meaning. it is unfortunately very common for survivors to at some point feel their life as a whole is completely hopeless or meaningless. ...as if it's been ruined, they'll never be okay, or that they only bring pain to the world. they can experience a level of despair that most cannot even conceptualize. additionally, many may find themselves wrestling with the idea of a god or any religion, even while trying to practice a faith they know well. they may turn against all belief because they can't reconcile the abuse they went through and what they were taught about a loving, protective god or universe.
.
beyond faith, hope and 'life's meaning' are other major value systems jilted by trauma. what is good or bad, right or wrong, moral or immoral -- these are things many believe we're just born knowing. even if that were true, prolonged trauma can dramatically rewrite it all. a survivor can believe they are 'bad' or immoral just by virtue of being exposed to it. they may've been taught abuse/pain feels good or is something done out of love and care. abusers proficient in psychological abuse can even convince a survivor that sexual abuses are 'good' or 'special' even. without being too upsetting, you can already see how one's moral compass and sense of right and wrong can be turned upside down while being hurt by someone with complete power over them. survivors may even believe it's "right" for them to suffer or be hurt, and a "good" thing when they're self-destructive -- as if that's what's "supposed to happen" or "what they deserve". sigh. it is heavy stuff.
.
as a survivor gets older and breaks free of their abuse, all of these "systems of meaning" can become convoluted beyond recognition - especially after exposure to a different way by friends/family. [continued in comments!]

we do this because it matters. parents are students too.

text:
it's not your fault, no matter what they say. it's not a survivor's fault and it's okay to take your time healing the wounds. it's okay to still have wounds that you could not get over. you and only you are the one who can decide what you should feel about your harassment, what step you wish to take and when you wish to speak up.

many brave women are speaking up about the abuse of their personal space and their consent and we admire their courage. it takes immense strength to speak up about sexual harassment and fuzia supports each survivor. 
if you wish to share your own story with the world, you can message us and we will publish it anonymously (or publicly if you wish to). we stand in solidarity with you, not and always.

many brave women are speaking up about the abuse of their personal space and their consent and we admire their courage. it takes immense strength to speak up about sexual harassment and fuzia supports each survivor. 
if you wish to share your own story with the world, you can message us and we will publish it anonymously (or publicly if you wish to). we stand in solidarity with you, not and always.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
a few days ago someone said to me (not really asked, because they don't want an actual answer), if you don't want me to say obscene things to you, then why do you post obscene pictures for the world to see? 
tell me again how cleavage is obscene and asking for it!

i understand some cultures find that obscene, but they are also cultures that respect women, so i asked what is going on in the world of social media where it has become the normal for men and women to be sexually objectified online? i'm trying to not let it bother me but it is so infuriating when body positivity is misconstrued as wanting sexual attention.

photo description: jessica has her brown hair down and is wearing black thin frames glasses. she is smiling and looking downwards so her eyes appear slightly closed.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
one of the most common blockages that people experience in relationships is not being able to open their hearts to hear and accept uncomfortable truths. hearing the truth is not always going to be pleasant. what will allow universal love to flow through you is finding your ways to connect to your heart when you receive well-intentioned messages so you can honor it and learn from the experience instead of taking the message as a punishment. 
if your partner or loved ones want to speak her/his truth to you, it‚Äôs crucial not to get blinded by the pain you feel within and appreciate her/his efforts for expressing what they perceive. once we open our hearts to others to share fears, challenges, and desires without judgment or accusations, we will feel more empowered and the relationship or friendship will gradually become stronger and more compassionate.

the core strength of a conscious relationship relies on allowing others to be themselves while experiencing their own journeys. if you are struggling on this topic, send us a message. sometimes one single session can transform & save your relationship. much love to all of you üíñüêâüåé #weeding #couples #instagood #love #session #help #energy #spiritualawakening #empoweringwomen #metoo #yvrwedding #world #higherconsciousness #eclipse369 #parenting

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically

carole cadwalladr

text:
when i was 15, i signed a contract binding my virginity to god, i remember this night at youth group so vividly. i sat there in a group of my peers all talking about why our first time should be special and why it was important to wait until we were married to have sex; using analogies like each sexual encounter as a ‚Äòbite out of your apple‚Äô, ‚Äúwhy would you want to give your husband a half eaten apple, or worse, a core!‚Äù.
.
inside, i was squirming, nauseated, simultaneously paralyzed and wanting to run away. what did it mean if bites had already been taken from your apple, what did it mean if they weren‚Äôt taken by choice?
.
throughout my teenage years, i remember having conversations about sex with my group of best friends, hearing stories of their first times and how magical it all sounded. i remember my best friend telling me about her first time and feeling so deeply jealous, not jealous that she‚Äôd had sex, but jealous that she‚Äôd gotten that magical moment of offering up her sacred virginity to someone she trusted, someone who cared for her and someone who asked first.
.
i knew i would never experience this.
i knew i couldn‚Äôt get back what was taken from me.
i felt rotten, nothing but an apple core.
i felt that no one would want me.
.
i truly, deeply believe that the concept of virginity is so deeply damaging to young people (womxn especially). it‚Äôs sexist, heteronormative, and contributes to rape culture. the current concept of virginity, erases queer and transfolk, and frames a womxn‚Äôs worth as inversely proportional to the number of penis‚Äôs that have been inside her.
.
here‚Äôs the thing. we can change this narrative. we can teach our children that their value isn‚Äôt less because of who or how many people they‚Äôve had sex with, we can teach our children that the most important thing about any sexual relationship is consent and respect.
.
if i could go back and tell my 15 year old self one thing that night, it would be ‚Äúyou‚Äôre not an apple darling, you‚Äôre a fucking diamond‚Äù.

text: women's black out day 25. tonight i was talking to a friend, a good man of a different culture, still an american. i brought up another friend, and good man of a similar culture also an american. something to be proud of, yet i find it important as well to regard the cultures stemmed from. i didn't mean to sound ignorant trying to introduce my friends to each other, they're both incredibly great, and just cool to talk to. it's just there's parts of my family and background of ancestors i'm not exposed to accurately in this country educationally, spiritually, ect. and it's upsetting to me. i don't understand how hard you've worked for your citizenship. however i do know that pieces of home are important to maintain humanity and personhood. both educated kind people are inspiring in various ways and i respect them as humans, carriers of their culture and americans. all of that is something to be proud of. regardless of how disturbing the sherbert jerk face is behaving. i know the various reasons to move here are unimaginable due to no-one can view the world through anothers perspective. understandings and tolerance and comprises can be met, but we never 100% know all the outlooks and reasoning behind them even amongst our closest confidants. i'm proud to have met both very different, awesome people. as well as finding you inspiring, it's cool to learn of other cultures, and parts of the world i have yet to venture to, to have an entirely different experience. how hard you fought for citizenship means a lot, it means a lot that you're here exposing your kindness and sense of belonging throughout this disaster. it is ours. the whole world, and our country needs to take this opportunity to make it known. #voteblue #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors #america #youarebeautiful

text:
persephone‚Äôs dancer rising (base only)
hand-carved alabaster stone

even more progress... and more... and more... and more and more... her face is beginning to shape and state back.

this part of the piece, the base, is a conglomeration of ancient goddess forms from throughout our ancestral past, rising up to hold the phoenix wing aloft. 
in process, a few more details and i have only 5 more days to go. 
this piece is meant as a trophy of triumph, a modern nike, presented to all women who have endured, (silently, painfully, sometimes with strength, other times with weakness, always courageously, and always without expressed informed consent) sexual assault.
it represents your futures beyond this era (that could end tomorrow or next year but certainly within your lifetime). it is the triumph that is inevitable for all women.

text:
i have always wondered 
why eve, the woman, 
is blamed 
for the downfall
of man.
maybe she took the fruit
because she craved 
the unknown.
maybe she wanted 
something of her own,
if only for a moment. 
see, there is a primal calling
deep inside a woman.
some choose to hear it,
some do not.
maybe she craved
wisdom more 
than she feared 
the consequence.
maybe she bore the pain 
because knowing was
better than wondering.
truth be told, 
i think we are better for it. 
i‚Äôd rather know 
my strength
through struggle.
i‚Äôd rather make beauty 
from ashes.
because those 
are the moments 
when i feel closest 
to god. ‚ú®üçÉ
